DataChallenge

Di Wu

2023-03-29

Background

The Etna Township Trustees appointed fifteen (15) community residents to the Community Advisory Committee to help guide the creation of the Township’s next comprehensive plan.

The Etna Township Comprehensive Plan Community Advisory Committee meets on the 2nd Wednesday of each month beginning at 6:00pm. The public is encouraged to attend. The meeting is held at the Etna Township building, 51 Liberty Street.

Together with Neighborhood Strategies (our planning consultant), the Community Advisory Committee has drafted the following public survey. Survey questions were designed to help the committee gather information about public sentiment on a variety of issues affecting the future of the Etna Township. Questions asked for basic demographic information, as well as opinions regarding current and future services, and development within the community. One of the most important considerations when formulating a comprehensive plan is public input.

      if (MyData1[row_index, col_index] == MyData1[1, col_index]) {
        MyData1[row_index, col_index] <- "1"
      }

        MyData1[row_index, col_index] <- "0"
      }
    }

Q2: knn classification: Can we predict if a respondent is a farmer (Q9) based on their likelihood of selling property (Q11)?

library(caret)
library(class)
set.seed(10)
# creating training data as 80% of the dataset
MyData2 <- MyData1 %>% filter(!is.na(`Q9_Response`))%>% filter(!is.na(`Q11_Open-Ended Response`))
random_sample <- createDataPartition(MyData2$`Q11_Open-Ended Response`, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
# generating training dataset
train <- MyData2[random_sample, ]
# generating testing dataset
test <- MyData2[-random_sample, ]
test_x <- select(test, `Q11_Open-Ended Response`)
test_y <- test$`Q9_Response`  
train_x <- select(train, `Q11_Open-Ended Response`)   
train_y <- train$`Q9_Response`
pred1 = knn(train_x,test_x,train_y,k=3)
test_mis_k <- c()
# for each K=i, fit the knn, find the prediction, 
# calculate the misclassification, store it in the ith item of vector misclassification
for(i in 1:62){
  predicted <- knn(train_x,test_x,train_y ,k=i)
  ConMat <- table(test_y,predicted)
  TN <- ConMat[1,1]
  FP <- ConMat[1,2]
  FN <- ConMat[2,1]
  TP <- ConMat[2,2]
  test_mis_k[i] <-(FP+FN) / sum(ConMat)
}

plot(test_mis_k)

which.min(test_mis_k)
## [1] 1
min(test_mis_k)
## [1] 0.05882353

When K=3, the KNN classification outperforms logistic regression with a misclassification rate 0.05882353.

Q4: Clustering:How can we group observations in MyData1 based on the number of years living in the Township (Q3)?

library(cluster)
library(factoextra)
data_cluster <- MyData1[,c("Q3_0 - 4 Years", "Q3_5 - 9 Years", "Q3_10 - 19 Years", "Q3_20 - 39 Years", "Q3_Over 40 Years", "Q3_I do not live in the Township")]
fviz_nbclust(data_cluster , kmeans, method = "wss")

model_clustering <- kmeans(data_cluster, centers = 7)

The first dimension (Dim.1) usually captures the largest proportion of the total variance in the data, while the second dimension (Dim.2) captures the second-largest proportion. The Q3_20-39 Years shows the highest Dim1 which is also over 90% of the total variance in the data. Categories that are close together along a dimension are more similar, while those farther apart are more different. This plot shows people live in 0-4 years and 5-9 years share the similar traits and people live for 20-39 years or 10-19 years seems to have a different group attribute than other groups.

Conclusion

KNN classification (K=3) is more effective than logistic regression for predicting Q8_Response, with a lower misclassification rate of 0.05882353. Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) has a classification accuracy of 1, indicating perfect prediction on the test set. However, be cautious with this result as it could be due to overfitting, and further validation with additional data is necessary. The Multiple Correspondence Analysis (MCA) plot suggests that the first dimension (Dim.1) captures the majority of the variance in the data, with Q3_20-39 Years contributing the most to this dimension. This indicates that the age group of 20-39 years has distinct characteristics when compared to other age groups in the dataset. The MCA plot also shows that residents who have lived in Etna Township for 0-4 years and 5-9 years share similar traits, while those who have lived there for 10-19 years or 20-39 years form a separate group with different attributes. This suggests that there may be underlying factors, such as lifestyle or community preferences, that influence these differences.

We might speculate that the town’s demographic makeup or geographic location could be contributing to the observed patterns in the data. Further analysis of the township’s characteristics, such as population size, employment opportunities, and recreational facilities, may help explain the observed differences between the age groups.

In summary, the analysis of Etna Township data reveals distinct patterns in the characteristics of residents based on their length of residence. The KNN classification and LDA models effectively predict Q8_Response, though additional validation is needed to ensure their robustness. Future research should investigate the underlying factors driving these differences and consider additional demographic or geographic variables to better understand the unique characteristics of Etna Township.
